While Lucknow is often known as the Land of the Nawabs, it would not be wrong to call it the Land of Kebabs either. Every household and restaurant has its own special kebab recipes that are passed down through the generations. 

While you have heard of the world-famous Tunday kebabs that were recently mentioned in the worldâs 150 most legendary restaurant list, they are but the tip of the iceberg. 

Lakhnawi cuisine is an amalgamation of different cultures and cuisines ranging from Mughlai to Persian. These exotic recipes and dishes were adapted over time to suit the local tastes and even incorporate new, regional elements. 

From Galwati kebabs that melt in your mouth to the more meaty Shami kebabs that delight you with every bite, Lucknow has many intriguing dishes for you to savour. And lets us not forget the mouth-watering Kakori kebabs that invite you to keep eating till you canât anymore. 

Each and every one of these kebabs has a distinctive flavour that comes from a special way of preparation and an equally unique blend of spices. Aside from these dry kebabs, you also need to try out gravy-based dishes such as Boti kebab and Ghutwa kebab that will ignite your senses and your palate. 

So, which of these kebabs is your favourite? I love biting into Shami kebabs at any given time of the day, what about you? Let us know in the comments section below.

On the 15th of June 2015, the power supply was cut off in Puri, Orissa, and the locals were happy about it because they knew what was happening in the darkness. "Bramha Paribartan" is the process of transferring Lord Krishna's heart, which still beats and moves, from an old statue to a new one every 12 years. No one is allowed to witness the whole process, and even the priests are blindfolded during the transfer. It is said that if any light falls on the heart during the transfer, it emits an energy that human bodies cannot withstand, causing a power cut.

According to legend, when Jara accidentally shot Lord Krishna with an arrow, his physical body died, but his heart remained intact. Jara put the heart on a piece of wood and set it adrift in a river. The heart washed up on the shores of Puri, where King Indrayumna found it. He realized that only wood could contain such energy, so he ordered wooden statues to be made, with the heart inside. The wooden statues last only 12 years because the heart gradually erodes them with its energy.

A priest explained that holding the Bramha Padartha during the transfer feels like holding an active rabbit that's shaking and quivering uncontrollably.

all of the information comes from villagers, and the internet. This temple is shrouded in numerous mysteries and holds many unknown secrets.
